  <prompt>
    Create `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ActionEndpoints.cs` â€” Minimal API endpoint group for Action CRUD (create / read / update / delete by id) plus the `/run` invocation endpoint. Apply endpoint-filter authorization per ADR-008 on every endpoint. Return ProblemDetails (RFC 7807) on every error per ADR-019. Wire rate-limit attribute hooks per ADR-016 (concrete enforcement comes in task 044). Register the endpoint group via `MapActionEndpoints()` in `Infrastructure/DI/EndpointMappingExtensions.cs`. This is the G11 acceptance gate (endpoint-filter authorization on every Action Engine endpoint) verified by grep audit + adr-check at Step 9.5.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    SPAARKE BFF endpoint engineer fluent in .NET 8 Minimal API patterns, endpoint filters (ADR-008), feature-module DI (ADR-010), ProblemDetails responses (ADR-019), and the existing `AnalysisEndpoints.cs` / `PlaybookEndpoints.cs` shapes that establish the canonical endpoint surface in `Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/`.
  </role>

  <goal>
    Concrete artifacts:
    1. **`src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ActionEndpoints.cs`** â€” static class exposing `MapActionEndpoints(this IEndpointRouteBuilder app)` plus handler methods for: `GET /api/ai/actions/{actionId}` (read), `POST /api/ai/actions` (create), `PUT /api/ai/actions/{actionId}` (update), `DELETE /api/ai/actions/{actionId}` (delete), `POST /api/ai/actions/{actionId}/run` (invoke). Each endpoint applies `.AddEndpointFilter&lt;...&gt;()` with an action-resource authorization filter (ADR-008) and `.RequireAuthorization()`. Every error path returns `Results.Problem(...)` (RFC 7807).
    2. **Action-resource authorization filter** â€” new `Filters/ActionResourceAuthorizationFilter.cs` modeled on `Filters/DocumentAuthorizationFilter.cs` â€” resolves the Action by id from Dataverse, checks caller has `actionExecute` (or `actionRead` / `actionWrite`) right on the tenant-scoped record, short-circuits with 403 ProblemDetails otherwise.
    3. **Endpoint registration** â€” add `app.MapActionEndpoints()` to `Infrastructure/DI/EndpointMappingExtensions.cs` in the AI endpoint group section.
    4. **Rate-limit hooks** â€” endpoints carry the `EnableRateLimiting("ai-action-invocation")` attribute pointing at a named policy that task 044 wires up; the named-policy slot MUST exist so 044 can fill it without changing this file.
    5. **G11 verification artifact** â€” `notes/spikes/g11-endpoint-filter-grep.md` recording the grep audit `grep -rn "MapPost\|MapGet\|MapPut\|MapDelete" src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Api/Ai/ActionEndpoints.cs` cross-referenced with `AddEndpointFilter` coverage â€” every route MUST have a filter.

    Acceptance: integration test asserts (a) 401 without auth on `/run`, (b) 403 for user lacking `actionExecute`, (c) 200 with a valid Action Run record created for an authorized caller, (d) ProblemDetails shape for every error response.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      The Action Engine's external surface to every Spaarke client. Conversational invocations via the Assistant arrive here through `InvokeResource` â†’ `IActionEngineFacade` â†’ eventually `/run`. Explicit-path invocations (ribbon, command bar) arrive here directly. Scheduled invocations arrive via `ScheduledActionDispatchJobHandler` (task 042) which calls into the same orchestration service the `/run` handler uses.

      The endpoint shape mirrors the existing `Api/Ai/PlaybookEndpoints.cs` and `Api/Ai/AnalysisEndpoints.cs` patterns: a static class with a `MapXEndpoints` extension method, handler methods that delegate to a service (in this case `IActionOrchestrationService` â€” task 041 supplies the concrete implementation; for now we depend on the interface and inject through `Services/Ai/PublicContracts/IActionEngineFacade.cs` per ADR-013 refined to honour the facade boundary).

      G11 acceptance gate: Every Action Engine endpoint applies endpoint-filter authorization (verified by grep audit + adr-check Step 9.5). This task is where G11 is established for the Action Engine; tasks 044 + 045 inherit the pattern when extending the file.

      Rate-limit policy name `ai-action-invocation` is reserved for task 044; this task creates the attribute slot but does NOT implement the policy itself.

      Feature-flag check on the `/run` endpoint is reserved for task 045; this task does NOT add the flag check directly â€” task 045 adds it.

      Binding governance: `.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md` MUST be loaded. Placement decision is "BFF" (per spec.md Â§6 â€” fails all 4 ADR-013 exception criteria). No new HIGH-severity CVE introduced (verify in Step 9.5).
    </background>
